Cs||FP||cp|8|AT|^B@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|Therefore, I am a very aggressive preempter. Some experts are not. It's a matter of style. You must decide which style is most appropriate for yourself. |
PG| ***** 2 ***** |


AT|

However, you should not think that aggressive preempting is only appropriate for advanced players who tend to play their cards better than intermediates. In fact, the opposite is true. In this lesson I will discuss at length the two important considerations.|
PG| ***** 3 ***** |


AT|

The first consideration is whether you should preempt. The second consideration is how much to preempt. We all know the traditional advice. However, as you will see, the important factors that influence us will sometimes dictate that we preempt with a non-traditional hand at a non-traditional level. |
PG| ***** 4 ***** |


AT|

The first order of business is to debunk the two popular misconceptions regarding preempts. They are:|
PG| ***** 5 ***** |


Cs|1|cp|4|fp|1|at|

^-{          Thou shalt not have a 4-card major on the side          }
^-|fp||cp||
pg| ***** 6 ***** |


at|
^-and

^-|fp|1|cp|4|cs|1|at|^-{    Do not preempt with a void    }
^-|
pg| ***** 7 ***** |


cp||fp||at|

^B@2Neither is accurate as long as you understand the situation. Would I preempt with a major suit of ace-queen-ten-nine on the side in addition to my long suit? Of course not.|
PG| ***** 8 ***** |


at|

^*BMM: ^*NMr. Bergen, in the lesson, convincingly debunk both conventional wisdoms and follows with "Important Factors When Preempting." Among many, in order of importance, they are listed next.|
PG| ***** 9 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Distribution particularly the distribution in the 3 other suits.|
PG| ***** 10 ***** |


AT| 

Vulnerability. You are not vulnerable and the opponents are vulnerable is the best of all. But don't overreact to vulnerability.|
PG| ***** 11 ***** |


AT|
  
Seat or position. First seat is a very good time to preempt with a weak hand. The second seat is not as desirable as first seat for preempting. The third seat is a wonderful time to preempt'even better than first seat. Mr. Bergen strongly recommends preempting very aggressively in third seat, especially when not vulnerable. And then there is fourth seat. A fourth seat weak 2-bid does exist but it is a strong preempt.|
PG| ***** 12 ***** |


AT|

^B@2^*BMM: ^*NPlease do not avoid making a fourth seat strong preempt until you get to read his logic.|
PG| ***** 13 ***** |


AT| 

The next factor is the rank of the suit. "A spade preempt is very effective because the opponents cannot bid a suit at the same level that you did. In general it is great to preempt in a major. But do not overlook preempts in a minor."|
PG| ***** 14 ***** |


AT|

^B@2^*BMM: ^*NNext is suit quality. Let us hear it directly from him.|
PG| ***** 15 ***** |


cp|8|AT|

^B@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|No one is saying you should wait for a perfect preempt in order to preempt. If you did, you would be left at the altar forever because perfect preempts, just like perfect occasions, are rare.  What is a 'perfect' preempt? It's a hand with a long strong suit. What do I mean by that? I like to have at least 4 of the top 6 cards. I prefer the suit to be "topless" ' to not have the ace. (^*BMM: ^*NPHonest, I did not inserted the word in quotations. But okay, I added the quotes merely to emphasize its importance -:).) A perfect preempt has little, if any, defense. So the perfect preempt would be a suit headed by QJ109, KJ109, or KQJ10. You want strength in the middle. Also I would like good distribution. I don't want to have 6-3-2-2 or 7-2-2-2 distribution. I want some short suits on the side. 6-3-3-1 with a suit headed by KQJ10 ' lovely. And if you give me a 4-card side suit and even a void, that is nirvana. One more consideration regarding the perfect preempt. I would prefer to have no honors on the side.|
PG| ***** 16 ***** |


AT|

^B@2^*BMM: ^*NNext Mr. Bergen details the flaws in a preempt hand which we should be aware of. And he says, "You will not get a perfect preempt very often. Your hand will have flaws. Your trump suit will have some holes in it. Your outside distribution may be the flattest it could be. The wrong vulnerability is a flaw. It's fine to still preempt, but you would rather have as few flaws as possible. If your primary suit is questionable and you have an outside suit that is very strong, that's a significant flaw. That suggests that maybe your side does not belong in your long suit."|
PG| ***** 17 ***** |


AT|

